    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-02-24T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-02-24T13:00:00-05:00" n="126"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                <head>126. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the United
                        Kingdom</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d126fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 684A.85322/2–2456. Secret. Received at 5:10 p.m. Repeated to Cairo,
                        Amman, Damascus, Beirut, Tel Aviv, Paris, Jerusalem, Baghdad, Jidda, and
                        Ankara.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-02-24T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1956—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3580. Embassy today conveyed to Foreign Office substance instructions repeated in
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 4766<note n="2" xml:id="d126fn2"
                        >Printed as telegram 2000, <ref target="#d120">Document 120</ref>.</note> as
                    well as text Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JE1">Johnston</persName>’s letter
                    to <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 4765<note n="3" xml:id="d126fn3">Printed as telegram 1999,
                            <ref target="#d119">Document 119</ref>.</note>). Foreign Office
                    considers instructions admirable and expects send instructions along similar <pb
                        facs="0263" n="235" xml:id="pg_235"/> lines to U.K. Embassies Amman, Beirut,
                    Cairo, Damascus and Tel Aviv tonight. Embassies will be told consult U.S. and
                    French colleagues.</p>
                <p>Embassy presumes Department has learned from British Embassy, Washington of
                    reports (1) from British Embassy Cairo that <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName> advises against <persName corresp="#p_JE1"
                        >Johnston</persName>’s visiting area at this time on grounds it would give
                    opportunity to those who wish sabotage <persName corresp="#p_JE1"
                        >Johnston</persName> plan, (confirming <persName corresp="#p_FM1"
                        >Fawzi</persName>’s remarks reported Cairo’s 1559<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d126fn4">
                        <ref target="#d92">Document 92</ref>.</note>) and (2) from British Embassy
                    Amman that Jordan Prime Minister told British Ambassador <gloss target="#t_HKJ1"
                        >HKJ</gloss> intends inform Syria, Lebanon and Egypt of Jordan’s desire
                    raise at Arab League Council meeting scheduled mid March question of answer to
                    be given Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JE1">Johnston</persName>. Jordan Prime
                    Minister pointed out to Duke he hoped this would demonstrate good faith of
                        <gloss target="#t_HKJ1">HKJ</gloss> and strengthen hands of Western powers
                    in restraining Israelis from “causing further incidents” or recommencing work on
                    Banat Yakub.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Aldrich</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
